editorial:
**Approach — Bellman-Ford with k+1 iterations**: Each iteration extends the path by one edge. After `k+1` iterations, `dist[dst]` is the cheapest using at most k+1 edges (i.e., at most k stops).

Key detail: take a snapshot of `dist` at the start of each iteration so a freshly-relaxed value isn't reused within the same pass.

```javascript
function cheapestKStops(n, flights, src, dst, k) {
  let dist = new Array(n).fill(Infinity);
  dist[src] = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i <= k; i++) {
    const prev = dist.slice();
    for (const [u, v, w] of flights) {
      if (prev[u] === Infinity) continue;
      if (prev[u] + w < dist[v]) dist[v] = prev[u] + w;
    }
  }
  return dist[dst] === Infinity ? -1 : dist[dst];
}
```

**Time**: O(k * E). **Space**: O(n).

